WEBVTT

00:07.202 --> 00:10.568
Maybe you've uttered the phrase, uh-oh, trouble up ahead.

00:10.608 --> 00:15.957
Suppose you're watching an episode of America's Funniest Home Videos.

00:17.098 --> 00:28.097
You see a clip of a guy, a drunk guy, handing his beer can to a friend, and then he climbs on a bike and he starts pedaling quickly, furiously, towards a ramp.

00:28.798 --> 00:31.643
As you're watching that, you say, uh-oh, trouble up ahead.

00:31.683 --> 00:33.746
And then the guy crashes.

00:34.306 --> 00:37.910
He doesn't get hurt, there are no injuries, but he looks silly when he crashes.

00:38.511 --> 00:42.755
And so you laugh along with the audience on America's funniest home videos.

00:44.758 --> 00:50.144
I'm sure you've seen people do stupid things that make you laugh and say, uh-oh, trouble up ahead.

00:50.184 --> 00:56.671
And I'm also sure that you've seen people do foolish or wicked things that don't make you laugh.

00:57.532 --> 01:02.898
But instead fill you with sorrow and grief, you say, oh, trouble up ahead.

01:04.098 --> 01:08.263
You may have experienced a family member or a friend make a bad decision.

01:08.323 --> 01:12.769
And you know the consequences of that bad decision will not be good.

01:13.550 --> 01:15.092
You see trouble up ahead.

01:15.152 --> 01:22.782
That's what Jesus sees when he criticizes the Pharisees and scribes in today's Bible reading.

01:24.083 --> 01:30.572
When Jesus uses the word woe, he sees trouble up ahead for people making bad decision.

01:30.972 --> 01:32.434
He knows that they will suffer

01:32.770 --> 01:35.633
horrible consequences for decisions that they're making.

01:37.675 --> 01:43.682
In today's reading, Jesus expresses, whoa, and this is no laughing matter.

01:43.922 --> 01:44.683
It's not funny.

01:45.884 --> 01:50.189
You're listening to Perdido Bay Methodist Church's podcast on the Gospel of Matthew.

01:51.230 --> 01:58.738
Today is Wednesday, March the 4th, and today we're reading Matthew chapter 24 verse 23 through 39.

02:02.850 --> 02:07.017
This is part of the last sermon that Jesus gives, and he gives this one in the temple.

02:07.057 --> 02:09.021
This is the last sermon in Matthew's Gospel.

02:09.081 --> 02:22.223
He preaches in the temple in Jerusalem, and in some ways this sermon, and we find the sermon in Matthew chapters 23 through 25, in some ways this sermon parallels his first sermon.

02:22.544 --> 02:23.706
This is Sermon on the Mount.

02:24.146 --> 02:26.290
That's in Matthew chapter 5 through 7.

02:27.650 --> 02:38.406
because the parallel is that Jesus begins His sermon on the Mount with blessings and He begins His sermon here in Matthew 23 with woes.

02:39.769 --> 02:53.810
The phrase blessed are that Jesus uses in Matthew chapter 5, blessed are, it's another way of saying congratulations or good for you or happy are you when this is happening.

02:54.818 --> 03:03.552
Jesus says that in Matthew 5 that you are blessed if you're poor in spirit and blessed if you hunger and thirst for righteousness.

03:03.612 --> 03:04.433
He's saying good for you.

03:04.513 --> 03:05.435
Congratulations.

03:05.455 --> 03:06.456
You're in a good place.

03:08.640 --> 03:20.338
Now in Matthew chapter 23, Jesus begins His sermon here with a series of woes, not words of congratulations, not words of blessings.

03:20.866 --> 03:23.169
Instead, Jesus is saying trouble up ahead.

03:23.649 --> 03:38.668
Jesus says, woe to you scribes and Pharisees who focus on tithing mint and dill and cumin, but who are ignoring the more important things in the law, such as focusing on justice, mercy, and faith.

03:40.210 --> 03:46.898
See, in other words, Jesus is saying trouble up ahead because you're making bad choices and you're going to suffer the consequences for this.

03:49.538 --> 03:57.307
Today's reading is the rest of chapter 23, and we're continuing Jesus' pronouncement of these woes.

03:58.328 --> 04:02.252
And he's referring to, he's addressing scribes and Pharisees.

04:02.593 --> 04:04.875
Scribes were the Bible scholars in the day.

04:05.516 --> 04:12.564
The Bible experts back in Jesus' day, the people who spent their time studying the Old Testament law, they were experts on the Old Testament law.

04:14.225 --> 04:18.290
The Pharisees, on the other hand, were a lay movement within Judaism.

04:18.690 --> 04:26.519
And it was, they were adherents who focused on living in pious and righteous ways before God.

04:28.060 --> 04:35.108
But in their pursuit of pleasing God, the scribes and the Pharisees, they were focusing on the wrong things.

04:36.029 --> 04:41.115
Jesus ends up calling them hypocrites, which means phonies, play actors.

04:42.376 --> 04:47.602
Jesus tells them, quote, woe to you scribes and Pharisees hypocrites.

04:48.418 --> 04:57.227
for you are like whitewashed tombs, which on the outside look beautiful, but inside are full of the bones of the dead and of all kinds of uncleanliness.

04:58.108 --> 05:05.236
So you also on the outside look righteous to others, but inside you're full of hypocrisy and lawlessness.

05:07.478 --> 05:14.546
And as you read through today's reading, you'll notice that chapter 23 ends with Jesus weeping over them.

05:14.946 --> 05:19.453
and weeping over the people of Jerusalem who keep rejecting his offer of grace and salvation.

05:20.374 --> 05:27.184
Jerusalem, Jerusalem Jesus cries out, the city that kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to it.

05:27.865 --> 05:33.494
How often have I desire to gather your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings?

05:34.275 --> 05:35.497
And you were not willing.

05:36.498 --> 05:38.922
See, your house is left to you desolate.

05:39.703 --> 05:44.530
For I tell you, you will not see again, see me again until you say,

05:44.610 --> 05:46.993
Blessed is the one who comes in the name of the Lord.

05:49.256 --> 06:04.175
As you read through chapter 23, I invite you to prayerfully reflect on whether Jesus would say to you, uh-oh, trouble up ahead with some of your choices and actions and attitudes.

06:04.195 --> 06:10.002
If you sense that Jesus would say, uh-oh, trouble up ahead, then turn from those ways, repent.

06:10.722 --> 06:14.307
and embrace the forgiveness and new life that Jesus is offering you.

06:14.708 --> 06:17.391
Change your ways and get them in line with God's will.

06:18.673 --> 06:27.466
Jesus is speaking these words here, not to condemn us, but He's giving us warnings so that we will avoid trouble up ahead.

06:27.526 --> 06:36.338
Trouble that will come to us if we insist on acting and thinking and foolish and ungodly ways.

06:38.082 --> 06:39.644
Remember what Jesus says in 317.

06:40.565 --> 06:41.326
John, 317.

06:41.926 --> 06:44.870
That's a great gospel to John's gospel.

06:44.930 --> 06:50.876
John, 317, Jesus said that he didn't come to condemn the world, but to save the world.

06:51.557 --> 06:59.286
And in today's reading, in Matthew chapter 23, Jesus is warning us of troubles that will come with sin.

07:00.427 --> 07:03.250
He's warning us because he wants to save us.

07:05.253 --> 07:06.514
My name is Scott Home.

07:06.594 --> 07:09.426
this podcast is produced by Kenny Stewart.

